  <data name="ProjectName_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Project name</value></data>
  <data name="ProjectName_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>A human-readable name for this project. Stored in the .levelproj file.</value></data>
  <data name="Operator_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Operator</value></data>
  <data name="Operator_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Name of the person performing the measurement. Recorded in the project file for traceability.</value></data>
  <data name="Notes_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Notes</value></data>
  <data name="Notes_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Free-text notes about this measurement or the object under test.</value></data>
  <data name="Object_SectionHeader.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Object</value></data>
  <data name="GeometryType_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Geometry type</value></data>
  <data name="GeometryType_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>The type of object being measured. Each geometry type uses a different measurement strategy and calculation method.</value></data>
  <data name="GeometryType_SurfacePlate.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Surface Plate</value></data>
  <data name="GeometryType_ParallelWays.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Parallel Ways</value></data>
  <data name="Width_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Width (mm)</value></data>
  <data name="Width_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Physical width of the surface plate in millimetres. Used to compute the step length between grid nodes.</value></data>
  <data name="Height_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Height (mm)</value></data>
  <data name="Height_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Physical height (depth) of the surface plate in millimetres.</value></data>
  <data name="Columns_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Columns</value></data>
  <data name="Columns_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Number of grid columns (nodes in the X direction). More columns increase measurement redundancy and resolution, but also the total number of steps.</value></data>
  <data name="Rows_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Rows</value></data>
  <data name="Rows_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Number of grid rows (nodes in the Y direction).</value></data>
  <data name="Strategy_SectionHeader.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Measurement Strategy</value></data>
  <data name="Strategy_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Strategy</value></data>
  <data name="Strategy_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>The traversal pattern used to visit all measurement points. Different strategies offer different levels of redundancy.</value></data>
  <data name="Strategy_FullGrid.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Full Grid (boustrophedon)</value></data>
  <data name="Strategy_UnionJack.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Union Jack</value></data>
  <data name="Strategy_ParallelWays.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Parallel Ways</value></data>
  <data name="StepCount_Label.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Steps</value></data>
  <data name="StepCount_Label_Tooltip.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Total number of individual level readings required for this configuration.</value></data>
  <data name="StartMeasurement_Button.Content" xml:space="preserve"><value>Start Measurement</value></data>
  <data name="Strategy_Help_Title.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Measurement Strategy</value></data>
  <data name="Strategy_Help_Body.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>A measurement strategy defines the order and direction in which the instrument visits each grid point. The Full Grid strategy traverses all rows first, then all columns, so each interior node is visited twice from independent directions. This redundancy is what makes the least-squares calculation possible. The Union Jack strategy adds diagonal traversals for higher redundancy.</value></data>
  <data name="FullGrid_Help_Title.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Full Grid (boustrophedon)</value></data>
  <data name="FullGrid_Help_Body.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>The instrument traverses all rows in alternating directions (boustrophedon = "as the ox ploughs"), then all columns in alternating directions. Every interior grid point is visited once during the row pass and once during the column pass. The two readings at each crossing point should agree — any difference is a closure error distributed by the solver.</value></data>
  <data name="UnionJack_Help_Title.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Union Jack</value></data>
  <data name="UnionJack_Help_Body.Text" xml:space="preserve"><value>Eight arms radiate from the centre node in the four cardinal (N, S, E, W) and four diagonal (NE, SE, SW, NW) directions. The Full variant adds a circumference ring connecting all arm tips, creating closed loops that the solver uses to detect and distribute closure errors. Higher redundancy than Full Grid, but requires more steps.</value></data>

